130. **Dilemma:** He must decide whether to plant a flower for a man who says, “I can’t forgive”—but the soil is already glowing;  
131. **Decision:** He plants it—then watches the man kneel—*and weep*;  
132. **Climax:** The flower blooms—then the man says, “I forgive you”—and vanishes;  
133. **Outcome:** Kaito realizes he’s not the gardener—he’s the *forgiveness*;  
134. **Clever Twist:** The flowers don’t bloom after forgiveness—they bloom *before* it;  
135. **Worldbuilding Feature:** The city is built on *unresolved pain*—and every flower is a memory of a wound that healed;  
136. **Scene:** Kaito stands in the garden—his own face in the petals.  

